1. Whickham dataset.

1. What variables are in this data set? outcome, smoker, age

2. How many observations are there and what does each represent? A data frame with 1314 observations on women for the following variables: 1) outcome: survival status after 20 years (alive or dead); 2) smoker: smoking status at baseline (No or Yes); 3) age: age (in years) at the time of the first survey/.

3. Create a table (use the R code below as a guide) and a visualization of the relationship between smoking status and outcome, ignoring age. What do you see? Does it make sense? It does not make sense because it shows that smokers have a greater likelihood of being alive than dead.

Whickham %>% count(smoker, outcome)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##   smoker outcome     n
##   <fct>  <fct>   <int>
## 1 No     Alive     502
## 2 No     Dead      230
## 3 Yes    Alive     443
## 4 Yes    Dead      139
Whickham %>% ggplot(aes(x = smoker, fill = outcome)) + 
geom_bar(position = 'fill') +
labs(y = '') +
theme_bw()

library(forcats)
library (dplyr)
Whickham %>% count(smoker, outcome)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##   smoker outcome     n
##   <fct>  <fct>   <int>
## 1 No     Alive     502
## 2 No     Dead      230
## 3 Yes    Alive     443
## 4 Yes    Dead      139
smokes <-tribble(
  ~smoker, ~outcome, ~value,
"No",   "Alive",    502,        
"No",   "Dead", 230,        
"Yes",  "Alive",    443,        
"Yes",  "Dead", 139,    
)
smokes %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_bar(aes(x = smoker, y = value, fill=outcome), stat = 'identity', position='dodge') +
  labs(x = 'smoker', y = 'outcome', 
       title = 'Smoker status and outcome')

4. Recode the age variable into an ordered factor with three categories: age <= 44, age > 44 & age <= 64, and age > 64. Now, recreate visualization from above, but facet on your new age factor. What do you see? Does it make sense? It is still surprising that smoker status doesn’t have much of an effect on outcome of dead or alive. Age has a much stronger effect. The probability of death increased dramatically with age, regardless of smoker status.

Whickham%>% 
  mutate(age_cat = case_when(age <= 44 ~"Younger than 44",
                   age > 44 & age <= 64 ~"Between 44 and 64",
                   age > 64~"Older than 64")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = smoker, fill = outcome)) + 
geom_bar(position = 'fill') +
labs(y = '') +
  facet_wrap(~age_cat)

Whickham%>% 
  mutate(age_cat = case_when(age <= 44 ~"Younger than 44",
                   age > 44 & age <= 64 ~"Between 44 and 64",
                   age > 64~"Older than 64"), age_cat= fct_relevel(age_cat,"Younger than 44", "Between 44 and 64","Older than 64" )) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = smoker, fill = outcome)) + 
geom_bar(position = 'fill') +
labs(y = '') +
  facet_wrap(~age_cat)

Exercise 2 The Central Limit Theorem states that the sampling distribution of sample means is approximately Normal, regardless of the distribution of your population. For this exercise our population distribution will be a Gamma(1,2) distribution, and we’ll show that the sampling distribution of the mean is in fact normally distributed. 1.
